<h2>In-class Lab 11.2<br />
</h2>
<ol type="I">
<li class="row0">
<p>
Exercise 1
</p>
<ol type="1">
<li class="row1">
<p>
If you are using a Linux virtual machine, or Mac OS X, open a terminal window.
On Windows, you should open a command-line window or command prompt.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Log in to your local MySQL server by issuing a command similar to the one below.
Use the <b>root</b> user name. The instructor will tell you the password for
lab computers and virtual machines.
</p>
<blockquote><code>
mysql -u root -p<br />
</code></blockquote>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
View existing database schemas by entering:
</p>
<blockquote><code>
show databases;<br />
</code></blockquote>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Create a new database schema named <b>bookstore</b>.
</p>
<blockquote><code>
create database bookstore;<br />
</code></blockquote>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Now create a regular user and grant them all rights on the bookstore schema.
</p>
<blockquote><code>
grant all on bookstore.* to astudent identified by 'password';<br />
</code></blockquote>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
If you wish you may also create a user with the same username as you have on
the class server.
</p>
<blockquote><code>
grant all on bookstore.* to djefferson identified by 'password';<br />
</code></blockquote>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
If your MySQL server also contains the <b>northwind</b> database schema, you
may wish to also grant both users access to it with the following commands:
</p>
<blockquote><code>
grant all on northwind.* to astudent;<br />
grant all on northwind.* to djefferson;<br />
</code></blockquote>
<p>
Note that you only use the "identified by" clause when creating a new user
account, not when granting that same user access to additional databases.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Now let's change the password of user <b>astudent</b> without altering any
privileges granted to the account:
</p>
<blockquote><code>
set password for astudent = password('astudent');
</code></blockquote>
<p>
Note that you can change the password of any existing account, including root,
using the "set password" command.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Now let's verify what user accounts exist on this MySQL server. To do so we
must change our default database to <b>mysql</b> and query the "user" table
using the following commands:
</p>
<blockquote><code>
use mysql;<br />
select user, host, password from user;<br />
</code></blockquote>
<p>
<p>
List the names of all valid users of this MySQL server:
</p>
&nbsp;<br />
<hr width="75%" />
<p>
What internet host or hosts can the user <b>root</b> connect from?
</p>
&nbsp;<br />
<hr width="75%" />
<p>
What internet host or hosts can the user <b>astudent</b> connect from?
</p>
&nbsp;<br />
<hr width="75%" />
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Type:&nbsp;&nbsp;<code>exit;</code>&nbsp;&nbsp;to log out of the MySQL server.
</p>
<p><hr width="50%" /></p>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li class="row0">
<p>
Exercise 2
</p>
<ol type="1">
<li class="row1">
<p>
Log in to your local MySQL server by issuing a command similar to the one below.
Use the <b>astudent</b> user name this time (password also astudent).
</p>
<blockquote><code>
mysql -u astudent -p<br />
</code></blockquote>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Set your default database to <b>bookstore</b> and verify this setting using a
built-in MySQL function as follows:
</p>
<blockquote><code>
use bookstore;<br />
select database();<br />
</code></blockquote>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Create a table in the <b>bookstore</b> database schema using the SQL
"CREATE TABLE" command. The table should be named "book" and should contain
the following columns:
</p>
<blockquote>
<table>
<tr>
<td><code><b><u>
Name</u></b></code></td>
<td><code><b><u>
Data Type</u></b>&nbsp;</code></td>
<td><code><b><u>
Length</u></b></code></td>
</tr><tr>
<td><code>
id</code></td>
<td><code>
int</code></td>
<td><code>
10 digits</code></td>
</tr><tr>
<td><code>
isbn</code></td>
<td><code>
char</code></td>
<td><code>
13 characters</code></td>
</tr><tr>
<td><code>
author&nbsp;</code></td>
<td><code>
varchar</code></td>
<td><code>
50 characters</code></td>
</tr><tr>
<td><code>
title</code></td>
<td><code>
varchar</code></td>
<td><code>
100 characters</code></td>
</tr><tr>
<td><code>
price</code></td>
<td><code>
float</code></td>
<td><code>
10 digits with 2 decimal places</code></td>
</tr>
</table>
</blockquote>
<p>
Make the "id" column the primary key of the table, and enable the "auto increment"
feature so it will be populated for you.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Verify that the table was created to specifications with the following commands:
</p>
<blockquote><code>
show tables;<br />
describe book;<br />
</code></blockquote>
</li>
<li class="row0">
<p>
Use the SQL INSERT command to add three rows (records) to the <b>book</b>
table. You may use real book names and authors or make some up, but please
don't just type in gibberish!
</p>
</li>
<li class="row0">
<p>
Show your instructor the results of your work by issuing SELECT and DESCRIBE
commands on your new table.
</p>
<p><hr width="50%" /></p>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
</body>
